<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ910225-0041</DOCNO><DOCID>910225-0041.</DOCID><HL>   Business Brief -- Sudbury Inc.:   Platt Unit Pleads Guilty   In Dispute Over Navy Job</HL><DATE>02/25/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A5B</SO><CO>   SUDS</CO><IN>POLLUTION CONTROL, WASTE MANAGEMENT SERVICES (POL)</IN><GV>JUSTICE DEPARTMENT (JUS)DEFENSE DEPARTMENT (DEF)</GV><LP>   Platt Manufacturing Corp., Dayton, Ohio, a Sudbury Inc.subsidiary, pleaded guilty and agreed to pay a fine for aone-count criminal information of mail fraud stemming from aU.S. Navy contract in 1986.   Platt said it pleaded guilty to the felony count to avoidthe costs of litigation relating to a dispute over crackedmetal connectors it sold to the Navy for use inaircraft-carrier launch systems.</LP><TEXT>   Platt said any cracked parts were recovered by the Navywithout incident. Under the agreement Platt will pay a fineof $210,000 and an additional $210,000 over the next twoyears to settle all claims with the Civil Division of theDepartment of Justice, including restitution for crackedconnectors parts.   The incident took place while Platt was under priorownership, and when Sudbury became aware of the matter itcooperated with authorities. Platt has continued to performsatisfactory work on a number of U.S. Navy contracts withoutproblem.   Sudbury is a Cleveland-based manufacturer.</TEXT></DOC>